\c 7
\p
\v 1 Then the residents of Kiriath Jearim came and took the LORD's chest of promise. They brought the chest to the house of Abinadab that was located on a hill. Then they purified Eleazar, son of Abinadab to become the responsible for the LORD's chest of promise.
\s1 The Israelites return to war with the Philistines
\p
\v 2 The chest was still saved in Kiriath Jearim during two years. During that time also all people of Israel mourned and cried out asking the LORD for help, because already so long He had allowed Israel to still be colonized by the Philistines.\f + \fr 7:2 \fk because... colonized \ft This phrase is implicit information that is made explicit in the TSI. See Judges 13:1\f*
\v 3 Then Samuel said to all of the people of Israel, "If you all sincerely want to return to worship the LORD with all your hearts, then throw away all of the foreign gods and statues of Ashtoreth that are among you all. Serve with sincerely  to the LORD and serve only Him, then He will free you all from the colonization of the Phillistines nation."
\v 4 Then the Israelites threw away the foreign god statues and the statues of Ashtoreth from their regions, and served only the LORD.
\p
\v 5 Then Samuel said, "Gather all of the Israelites to Mizpah, then I will pray to the LORD for you all."
\v 6 After the people of Israel gathered at Mizpah, they took water made ceremony where they poured it out as a sign of repentance that truly symbolized their souls  were truly  surrendered to the LORD. All day long they fasted and cry out asking fo forgiveness saying, "We have sinned against the LORD."
\p In this place Samuel begins to become judge for the people of Israel.
\p
\v 7 When the Philistines heard that Israel had gathered at Mizpah, then the five kings of the Philistines gathered their troops, and went to attack the people of Israel. When was heard that the Philistine army was coming, all of Israel was so afraid.
\v 8 They said to Samuel, "Pray continuously to the LORD our God, so that He helps and saves us from the attack of the Philistines nation!"
\v 9 Then Samuel took a suckling lamb and offered it entirely as a burnt sacrifice to the LORD. Samuel prayed to the LORD for the Israelites, and the LORD answered him.
\p
\v 10 At the time Samuel offered the burnt sacrifice, the Philistines approached to attack the them. But at that moment also, the LORD sent a sound like thunder  so hard from the sky as sign threatening againstthe Philistines people, so that they became panicked, and the Israelites defeated them.
\v 11 Starting from Mizpah, the people of Israel chase and kill the soldiers of the Philistines until to downstrem of  of Beth-car.
\s1 Making peace with Israel's enemies, and Samuel's Ministry
\p
\v 12 Then Samuel took a large and high stone, then placed it between Mizpah and Shen. He named that monument Ebenezer, because he said, "Until now the LORD has helped us."
\p
\v 13 In that way the Philistines were defeated, and after that they didn't enter the region of Israel to war any more. During the life of Smauel, the LORD continued to help the people of Israel so that nation of Philistines did not dare to attack them again.
\v 14 The Israelites succeed to take back all of the cities that had previously been taken by the Philistines, starting with the city of Ekron up to Gath. In that way the Israelites were able to take back all of their region. Peace also happened between the Israelites and the Amorites.
\p
\v 15 Samuel ruled as a judge over the people of Israel until he died.
\v 16 Every year Samuel went around from Bethel, Gilgal, and Mizpah. In each city Samuel resolve the cases that happened among the Israelites.
\v 17 Then Samuel returned to his house in Ramah. There he also judge cases among the Israelites. and built an altar to offer sacrifice to the LORD.